# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-vault-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data vault modeling makes no distinction between good and bad data ("bad" meaning not conforming to business rules).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] A data vault enterprise data warehouse provides both a single version of facts and a single source of truth.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The modeling method is designed to be resilient to change in the business environment where the data being stored is coming from, by explicitly separating structural information from descriptive attributes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data vault is designed to enable parallel loading as much as possible, so that very large implementations can scale out without the need for major redesign.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Unlike the star schema (dimensional modelling) and the classical relational model (3NF), data vault and anchor modeling are well-suited for capturing changes that occur when a source system is changed or added, but are considered advanced techniques which require experienced data architects.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Both data vaults and anchor models are entity-based models but anchor models have a more normalized approach.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In its early days, Dan Linstedt referred to the modeling technique, which was to become data vault, as *common foundational warehouse architecture* or *common foundational modeling architecture*.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In data warehouse modeling, there are two well-known competing options for modeling the layer where the data are stored.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Either you model according to Ralph Kimball, with conformed dimensions and an enterprise data bus, or you model according to Bill Inmon with the database normalized.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Both techniques have issues when dealing with changes in the systems feeding the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] For conformed dimensions, you also have to cleanse data (to conform it), and this is undesirable in several cases since this inevitably will lose information.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] detail-orientedthe detail-orientedThe detail-oriented Data Vault's philosophy is that all data is relevant data, even if it is not in line with established definitions and business rules.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] If data are not conforming to these definitions and rules, then that is a problem for the business, not the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The determination of data being "wrong" is an interpretation of the data that stems from a particular point of view that may not be valid for everyone, or at every point in time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Therefore, the data vault must capture all data, and only when reporting or extracting data from the data vault is the data being interpreted.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Another issue to which the data vault is a response is that, more and more, there is a need for complete auditability and traceability of all the data in the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Due to Sarbanes-Oxley requirements in the USA and similar measures in Europe, this is a relevant topic for many business intelligence implementations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The focus of any data vault implementation is complete traceability and auditability of all information.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] It is necessary to evolve the specification to include the new components, along with the best practices, in order to keep the EDW and BI systems current with the needs and desires of today's businesses.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data vault modeling was originally conceived by Dan Linstedt in the 1990s and was released in 2000 as a public domain modeling method.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In a series of five articles in The Data Administration Newsletter, the basic rules of the Data Vault method are expanded and explained.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] These contain a general overview, an overview of the components, a discussion about end dates and joins, link tables, and an article on loading practices.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] By using a data mining set of algorithms, links can be scored with confidence and strength ratings.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] They can be created and dropped on the fly in accordance with learning about relationships that currently don't exist.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The model can be automatically morphed, adapted, and adjusted as it is used and fed new structures.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Another view is that a data vault model provides an ontology of the Enterprise in the sense that it describes the terms in the domain of the enterprise (Hubs) and the relationships among them (Links), adding descriptive attributes (Satellites) where necessary.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Another way to think of a data vault model is as a graphical model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The data vault model actually provides a "graph-based" model with hubs and relationships in a relational database world.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In this manner, the developer can use SQL to get at graph-based relationships with sub-second responses.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Specialized satellites support temporal semantics.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] For example, an **effectiveness satellite** on a link records begin/end dates representing when the relationship is considered effective by the business.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In practice, Data Vault commonly serves as the historical integration layer, while star-schema information marts are projected from the Raw/Business Vault for performant analytics and simpler user access.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Hubs contain a list of unique business keys with low propensity to change.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Hubs also contain a surrogate key for each Hub item and metadata describing the origin of the business key.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The descriptive attributes for the information on the Hub (such as the description for the key, possibly in multiple languages) are stored in structures called Satellite tables, which will be discussed below.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] A hub is not allowed to contain multiple business keys, except when two systems deliver the same business key but with collisions that have different meanings.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Hubs should normally have at least one satellite.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This is an example of a hub-table containing cars, called "Car" (H_CAR).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The driving key is the vehicle identification number.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Associations or transactions between business keys (relating for instance the hubs for customer and product with each other through the purchase transaction) are modeled using link tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] These tables are basically many-to-many join tables, with some metadata.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Links can link to other links, to deal with changes in granularity (for instance, adding a new key to a database table would change the grain of the database table).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] For instance, if you have an association between customer and address, you could add a reference to a link between the hubs for product and transport company.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Referencing a link in another link is considered a bad practice, because it introduces dependencies between links that make parallel loading more difficult.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Since a link to another link is the same as a new link with the hubs from the other link, in these cases creating the links without referencing other links is the preferred solution (see the section on loading practices for more information).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Links sometimes link hubs to information that is not by itself enough to construct a hub.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This occurs when one of the business keys associated by the link is not a real business key.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] As an example, take an order form with "order number" as key, and order lines that are keyed with a semi-random number to make them unique.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The latter key is not a real business key, so it is no hub.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] However, we do need to use it in order to guarantee the correct granularity for the link.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] In this case, we do not use a hub with surrogate key, but add the business key "unique number" itself to the link.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This is done only when there is no possibility of ever using the business key for another link or as key for attributes in a satellite.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This construct has been called a 'peg-legged link' by Dan Linstedt on his (now defunct) forum.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Links contain the surrogate keys for the hubs that are linked, their own surrogate key for the link and metadata describing the origin of the association.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The descriptive attributes for the information on the association (such as the time, price or amount) are stored in structures called *satellite tables* which are discussed below.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This is an example for a link-table between two hubs for cars (H_CAR) and persons (H_PERSON).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The hubs and links form the structure of the model, but have no temporal attributes and hold no descriptive attributes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] These are stored in separate tables called *satellites*.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] These consist of metadata linking them to their parent hub or link, metadata describing the origin of the association and attributes, as well as a timeline with start and end dates for the attribute.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Where the hubs and links provide the structure of the model, the satellites provide the "meat" of the model, the context for the business processes that are captured in hubs and links.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] These attributes are stored both with regards to the details of the matter as well as the timeline and can range from quite complex (all of the fields describing a client's complete profile) to quite simple (a satellite on a link with only a valid-indicator and a timeline).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Usually the attributes are grouped in satellites by source system.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] However, descriptive attributes such as size, cost, speed, amount or color can change at different rates, so you can also split these attributes up in different satellites based on their rate of change.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] All the tables contain metadata, minimally describing at least the source system and the date on which this entry became valid, giving a complete historical view of the data as it enters the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] An effectivity satellite is a satellite built on a link, "and record[s] the time period when the corresponding link records start and end effectivity".
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This is an example for a satellite on the drivers-link between the hubs for cars and persons, called "Driver insurance" (S_DRIVER_INSURANCE).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Also included is a reference to a lookup- or reference table called R_RISK_CATEGORY containing the codes for the risk category in which this relationship is deemed to fall.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] (*) at least one attribute is mandatory.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] (**) sequence number becomes mandatory if it is needed to enforce uniqueness for multiple valid satellites on the same hub or link.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Reference tables are a normal part of a healthy data vault model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] They are there to prevent redundant storage of simple reference data that is referenced a lot.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Reference tables are referenced from Satellites, but never bound with physical foreign keys.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] There is no prescribed structure for reference tables: use what works best in your specific case, ranging from simple lookup tables to small data vaults or even stars.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] They can be historical or have no history, but it is recommended that you stick to the natural keys and not create surrogate keys in that case.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Normally, data vaults have a lot of reference tables, just like any other Data Warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This is an example of a reference table with risk categories for drivers of vehicles.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] It can be referenced from any satellite in the data vault.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] For now we reference it from satellite S_DRIVER_INSURANCE.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The ETL for updating a data vault model is fairly straightforward (see Data Vault Series 5 – Loading Practices).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] First you have to load all the hubs, creating surrogate IDs for any new business keys.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Having done that, you can now resolve all business keys to surrogate ID's if you query the hub.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The second step is to resolve the links between hubs and create surrogate IDs for any new associations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] At the same time, you can also create all satellites that are attached to hubs, since you can resolve the key to a surrogate ID.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Once you have created all the new links with their surrogate keys, you can add the satellites to all the links.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Since the hubs are not joined to each other except through links, you can load all the hubs in parallel.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Since links are not attached directly to each other, you can load all the links in parallel as well.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Since satellites can be attached only to hubs and links, you can also load these in parallel.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The ETL is quite straightforward and lends itself to easy automation or templating.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Problems occur only with links relating to other links, because resolving the business keys in the link only leads to another link that has to be resolved as well.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Due to the equivalence of this situation with a link to multiple hubs, this difficulty can be avoided by remodeling such cases and this is in fact the recommended practice.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data is never deleted from the data vault, unless you have a technical error while loading data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The data vault modelled layer is normally used to store data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] It is not optimised for query performance, nor is it easy to query by the well-known query-tools such as Cognos, Oracle Business Intelligence Suite Enterprise Edition, SAP Business Objects, Pentaho et al.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Since these end-user computing tools expect or prefer their data to be contained in a dimensional model, a conversion is usually necessary.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] For this purpose, the hubs and related satellites on those hubs can be considered as dimensions and the links and related satellites on those links can be viewed as fact tables in a dimensional model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] This enables you to quickly prototype a dimensional model out of a data vault model using views.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Note that while it is relatively straightforward to move data from a data vault model to a (cleansed) dimensional model, the reverse is not as easy, given the denormalized nature of the dimensional model's fact tables, fundamentally different to the third normal form of the data vault.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] The data vault methodology is based on SEI/CMMI Level 5 best practices.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] It includes multiple components of CMMI Level 5, and combines them with best practices from Six Sigma, total quality management (TQM), and SDLC.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Particularly, it is focused on Scott Ambler's agile methodology for build out and deployment.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data vault projects have a short, scope-controlled release cycle and should consist of a production release every 2 to 3 weeks.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Teams using the data vault methodology should readily adapt to the repeatable, consistent, and measurable projects that are expected at CMMI Level 5.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-vault-modeling] Data that flow through the EDW data vault system will begin to follow the TQM life-cycle that has long been missing from BI (business intelligence) projects.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:data-vault-modeling/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The **database schema** is the structure of a database described in a formal language supported typically by a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The term "schema" refers to the organization of data as a blueprint of how the database is constructed (divided into database tables in the case of relational databases).
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The formal definition of a database schema is a set of formulas (sentences) called integrity constraints imposed on a database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] These integrity constraints ensure compatibility between parts of the schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] All constraints are expressible in the same language.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] A database can be considered a structure in realization of the database language.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The states of a created conceptual schema are transformed into an explicit mapping, the database schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] This describes how real-world entities are modeled in the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] "A database schema specifies, based on the database administrator's knowledge of possible applications, the facts that can enter the database, or those of interest to the possible end-users." The notion of a database schema plays the same role as the notion of theory in predicate calculus.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] A model of this "theory" closely corresponds to a database, which can be seen at any instant of time as a mathematical object.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Thus a schema can contain formulas representing integrity constraints specifically for an application and the constraints specifically for a type of database, all expressed in the same database language.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In a relational database, the schema defines the tables, fields, relationships, views, indexes, packages, procedures, functions, queues, triggers, types, sequences, materialized views, synonyms, database links, directories, XML schemas, and other elements.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] A database generally stores its schema in a data dictionary.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Although a schema is defined in text database language, the term is often used to refer to a graphical depiction of the database structure.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In other words, schema is the structure of the database that defines the objects in the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In an Oracle Database system, the term "schema" has a slightly different connotation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The requirements listed below influence the detailed structure of schemas that are produced.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Certain applications will not require that all of these conditions are met, but these four requirements are the most ideal.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Each of the overlapping elements specified in the input mapping is also in a database schema relation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Source-specific elements that are associated with a source’s overlapping elements are passed through to the database schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Independent entities and relationships in the source data should not be grouped together in the same relation in the database schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In particular, source specific schema elements should not be grouped with overlapping schema elements, if the grouping co-locates independent entities or relationships.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] If any elements of the database schema are dropped then the database schema is not ideal.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Suppose we want a mediated schema to integrate two travel databases, Go-travel and Ok-flight.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In the context of Oracle Databases, a **schema object** is a logical data storage structure.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] An Oracle database associates a separate schema with each database **user**.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] A schema comprises a collection of schema objects.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Schema objects do not have a one-to-one correspondence to physical files on disk that store their information.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] However, Oracle databases store schema objects logically within a tablespace of the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] The data of each object is physically contained in one or more of the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] For some objects (such as tables, indexes, and clusters) a database administrator can specify how much disk space the Oracle RDBMS allocates for the object within the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] There is no necessary relationship between schemas and tablespaces: a tablespace can contain objects from different schemas, and the objects for a single schema can reside in different tablespaces.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] Oracle database specificity does, however, enforce platform recognition of nonhomogenized sequence differentials, which is considered a crucial limiting factor in virtualized applications.
[src:data-vault-modeling/database-schema] In Microsoft SQL Server, the default schema of every database is the dbo schema.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A **dimension** is a structure that categorizes facts and measures in order to enable users to answer business questions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Commonly used dimensions are people, products, place and time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] In a data warehouse, dimensions provide structured labeling information to otherwise unordered numeric measures.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The dimension is a data set composed of individual, non-overlapping data elements.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The primary functions of dimensions are threefold: to provide filtering, grouping and labelling.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] These functions are often described as "slice and dice".
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A common data warehouse example involves sales as the measure, with customer and product as dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The data can be sliced by removing all customers except for a group under study, and then diced by grouping by product.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A dimensional data element is similar to a categorical variable in statistics.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Typically dimensions in a data warehouse are organized internally into one or more hierarchies.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A slowly changing dimension is a set of data attributes that change slowly over a period of time rather than changing regularly e.g. address or name.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes can change over a period of time and that will get combined as a slowly changing dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension is a set of data attributes that have been physically referenced in multiple database tables using the same key value to refer to the same structure, attributes, domain values, definitions and concepts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimension cuts across many facts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are conformed when they are either exactly the same (including keys) or one is a proper subset of the other.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions are either identical or strict mathematical subsets of the most granular, detailed dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables are not conformed if the attributes are labeled differently or contain different values.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Conformed dimensions come in several different flavors.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] At the most basic level, conformed dimensions mean exactly the same thing with every possible fact table to which they are joined.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension table connected to the sales facts is identical to the date dimension connected to the inventory facts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a convenient grouping of typically low-cardinality flags and indicators.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] By creating an abstract dimension, these flags and indicators are removed from the fact table while placing them into a useful dimensional framework.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A junk dimension is a dimension table consisting of attributes that do not belong in the fact table or in any of the existing dimension tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The nature of these attributes is usually text or various flags, e.g. non-generic comments or just simple yes/no or true/false indicators.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] These kinds of attributes are typically remaining when all the obvious dimensions in the business process have been identified and thus the designer is faced with the challenge of where to put these attributes that do not belong in the other dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] One solution is to create a new dimension for each of the remaining attributes, but due to their nature, it could be necessary to create a vast number of new dimensions resulting in a fact table with a very large number of foreign keys.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer could also decide to leave the remaining attributes in the fact table but this could make the row length of the table unnecessarily large if, for example, the attribute is a long text string.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The solution to this challenge is to identify all the attributes and then put them into one or several junk dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] One junk dimension can hold several true/false or yes/no indicators that have no correlation with each other, so it would be convenient to convert the indicators into a more describing attribute.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] An example would be an indicator about whether a package had arrived: instead of indicating this as “yes” or “no”, it would be converted into "arrived" or "pending" in the junk dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The designer can choose to build the dimension table so it ends up holding all the indicators occurring with every other indicator so that all combinations are covered.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] This sets up a fixed size for the table itself which would be 2*x* rows, where *x* is the number of indicators.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] This solution is appropriate in situations where the designer would expect to encounter a lot of different combinations and where the possible combinations are limited to an acceptable level.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] In a situation where the number of indicators are large, thus creating a very big table or where the designer only expects to encounter a few of the possible combinations, it would be more appropriate to build each row in the junk dimension as new combinations are encountered.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] To limit the size of the tables, multiple junk dimensions might be appropriate in other situations depending on the correlation between various indicators.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Junk dimensions are also appropriate for placing attributes like non-generic comments from the fact table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Such attributes might consist of data from an optional comment field when a customer places an order and as a result will probably be blank in many cases.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Therefore, the junk dimension should contain a single row representing the blanks as a surrogate key that will be used in the fact table for every row returned with a blank comment field.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A degenerate dimension is a key, such as a transaction number, invoice number, ticket number, or bill-of-lading number, that has no attributes and hence does not join to an actual dimension table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions are very common when the grain of a fact table represents a single transaction item or line item because the degenerate dimension represents the unique identifier of the parent.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Degenerate dimensions often play an integral role in the fact table's primary key.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimensions are often recycled for multiple applications within the same database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] For instance, a "Date" dimension can be used for "Date of Sale", as well as "Date of Delivery", or "Date of Hire".
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] This is often referred to as a "role-playing dimension".
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be implemented using a view over the same dimension table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Usually dimension tables do not reference other dimensions via foreign keys.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] When this happens, the referenced dimension is called an outrigger dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Outrigger dimensions should be considered a data warehouse anti-pattern: it is considered a better practice to use some fact tables that relate the two dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A conformed dimensions is said to be a shrunken dimension when it includes a subset of the rows and/or columns of the original dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A special type of dimension can be used to represent dates with a granularity of a day.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dates would be referenced in a fact table as foreign keys to a date dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension primary key could be a surrogate key or a number using the format YYYYMMDD.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension can include other attributes like the week of the year, or flags representing work days, holidays, etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] It could also include special rows representing: not known dates, or yet to be defined dates.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The date dimension should be initialized with all the required dates, say the next 10 years of dates, or more if required, or past dates if events in the past are handled.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Time instead is usually best represented as a timestamp in the fact table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] When referencing data from a metadata registry such as ISO/IEC 11179, representation terms such as "Indicator" (a Boolean true/false value), "Code" (a set of non-overlapping enumerated values) are typically used as dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, using the National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) the data element name would be "PersonGenderCode" and the enumerated values might be "male", "female" and "unknown".
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] In data warehousing, a dimension table is one of the set of companion tables to a fact table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The fact table contains business facts (or measures), and foreign keys which refer to candidate keys (normally primary keys) in the dimension tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Contrary to fact tables, dimension tables contain descriptive attributes (or fields) that are typically textual fields (or discrete numbers that behave like text).
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] These attributes are designed to serve two critical purposes: query constraining and/or filtering, and query result set labeling.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension table rows are uniquely identified by a single key field.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] It is recommended that the key field be a simple integer because a key value is meaningless, used only for joining fields between the fact and dimension tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Dimension tables often use primary keys that are also surrogate keys.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Surrogate keys are often auto-generated (e.g. a Sybase or SQL Server "identity column", a PostgreSQL or Informix serial, an Oracle SEQUENCE or a column defined with AUTO_INCREMENT in MySQL).
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Although surrogate key use places a burden on the ETL system, pipeline processing can be improved, and ETL tools have built-in improved surrogate key processing.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The goal of a dimension table is to create standardized, conformed dimensions that can be shared across the enterprise's data warehouse environment, and enable joining to multiple fact tables representing various business processes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Over time, the attributes of a given row in a dimension table may change.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] For example, the shipping address for a company may change.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Kimball refers to this phenomenon as slowly changing dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Since many fact tables in a data warehouse are time series of observations, one or more date dimensions are often needed.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] One of the reasons to have date dimensions is to place calendar knowledge in the data warehouse instead of hard-coded in an application.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] While a simple SQL date-timestamp is useful for providing accurate information about the time a fact was recorded, it can not give information about holidays, fiscal periods, etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] An SQL date-timestamp can still be useful to store in the fact table, as it allows for precise calculations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Having both the date and time of day in the same dimension, may easily result in a huge dimension with millions of rows.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] If a high amount of detail is needed it is usually a good idea to split date and time into two or more separate dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A time dimension with a grain of seconds in a day will only have 86400 rows.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] A more or less detailed grain for date/time dimensions can be chosen depending on needs.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] As examples, date dimensions can be accurate to year, quarter, month or day and time dimensions can be accurate to hours, minutes or seconds.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] As a rule of thumb, time of day dimension should only be created if hierarchical groupings are needed or if there are meaningful textual descriptions for periods of time within the day (ex. “evening rush” or “first shift”).
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] If the rows in a fact table are coming from several time zones, it might be useful to store date and time in both local time and a standard time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] This can be done by having two dimensions for each date/time dimension needed – one for local time, and one for standard time.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] Storing date/time in both local and standard time, will allow for analysis on when facts are created in a local setting and in a global setting as well.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] The standard time chosen can be a global standard time (ex.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] UTC), it can be the local time of the business’ headquarters (ex.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimension-data-warehouse] CET), or any other time zone that would make sense to use.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional modeling always uses the concepts of facts (measures), and dimensions (context).
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Facts are typically (but not always) numeric values that can be aggregated, and dimensions are groups of hierarchies and descriptors that define the facts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] For example, sales amount is a fact; timestamp, product, register#, store#, etc. are elements of dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional models are built by business process area, e.g. store sales, inventory, claims, etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Because the different business process areas share some but not all dimensions, efficiency in design, operation, and consistency, is achieved using conformed dimensions, i.e. using one copy of the shared dimension across subject areas.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional modeling does not necessarily involve a relational database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The same modeling approach, at the logical level, can be used for any physical form, such as multidimensional database or even flat files.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] It is oriented around understandability and performance.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The dimensional model is built on a star-like schema or snowflake schema, with dimensions surrounding the fact table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The process of dimensional modeling builds on a 4-step design method that helps to ensure the usability of the dimensional model and the use of the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The basics in the design build on the actual business process which the data warehouse should cover.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Therefore, the first step in the model is to describe the business process which the model builds on.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] This could for instance be a sales situation in a retail store.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] To describe the business process, one can choose to do this in plain text or use basic Business Process Model and Notation (BPMN) or other design guides like the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] After describing the business process, the next step in the design is to declare the grain of the model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The grain of the model is the exact description of what the dimensional model should be focusing on.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] This could for instance be “An individual line item on a customer slip from a retail store”.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] To clarify what the grain means, you should pick the central process and describe it with one sentence.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Furthermore, the grain (sentence) is what you are going to build your dimensions and fact table from.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] You might find it necessary to go back to this step to alter the grain due to new information gained on what your model is supposed to be able to deliver.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The third step in the design process is to define the dimensions of the model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] The dimensions must be defined within the grain from the second step of the 4-step process.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensions are the foundation of the fact table, and is where the data for the fact table is collected.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Typically dimensions are nouns like date, store, inventory etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] These dimensions are where all the data is stored.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] For example, the date dimension could contain data such as year, month and weekday.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] After defining the dimensions, the next step in the process is to make keys for the fact table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] This step is to identify the numeric facts that will populate each fact table row.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] This step is closely related to the business users of the system, since this is where they get access to data stored in the data warehouse.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Therefore, most of the fact table rows are numerical, additive figures such as quantity or cost per unit, etc.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensional normalization or snowflaking removes redundant attributes, which are known in the normal flatten de-normalized dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Dimensions are strictly joined together in sub dimensions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] Snowflaking has an influence on the data structure that differs from many philosophies of data warehouses.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] 3NF databases suffer from performance problems when aggregating or retrieving many dimensional values that may require analysis.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] If you are only going to do operational reports then you may be able to get by with 3NF because your operational user will be looking for very fine grain data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] There are some arguments on why normalization can be useful.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] It can be an advantage when part of hierarchy is common to more than one dimension.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] For example, a geographic dimension may be reusable because both the customer and supplier dimensions use it.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] We still get the benefits of dimensional models on Hadoop and similar big data frameworks.
[src:data-vault-modeling/dimensional-modeling] However, some features of Hadoop require us to slightly adapt the standard approach to dimensional modelling.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:data-vault-modeling/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
